segments.text: Okay, this is an interview with Louis Pierre Phaneuf by Michelle Duran in his home in Kingwood, Texas, concerning the Vietnam War.
In the interest of accumulating knowledge about the war, I am going to donate this tape to the Texas A&M Oral History Collection in the University Archives.
Is that all right with you?
Yes, that will be fine.
Okay.
Okay, first of all, when and where were you born, if you don't mind?
I was born in Lynn, Massachusetts in August of 1944.
Okay, what about your education?
Did you go to college before you went?
No, I went to high school and I had one semester of college and then I dropped out.
So, why did you join the military?
Okay, well, after I got out of college, then I went to work for General Electric Company.

And then because of, at that time, we still had a draft in place, and it was just obvious that I was going to be drafted, so I thought I'd go into the service of my choice rather than the government's.
So I chose the United States Air Force.
When did you join?
In August of 1964.
Okay.
All right, so what about your training?
Where did you train?
Okay, well, everybody at that time in the Air Force went to basic training at Likeland Air Force Base in San Antonio.
Then after I got out of there, I went to Shepard Air Force Base up at, where that was.
I was up in the Panhandle of Texas, and there was a tech school up there for jet engine maintenance.
The reason I chose that was when I was working with General Electric, I was working on military jet engines with General Electric, so I thought it would be easy to pursue that within the Air Force.
So I went to a technical school up there for that.
And after that, I went to a pilot training base in Big Spring, Texas.
So, and when I was over there,
I was there for about 10 months, and at that time I just became dissatisfied with that particular part of the country, and I wanted to see more of the world and everything.
I chose to volunteer for Vietnam and go over there in a special group.
So that's how I ended up over there.
Before going over there, I went to Florida for special training.
Hi.
Okay, so where did you get sent in Vietnam?
Okay, we were stationed at Cam Ranh Bay, Vietnam, which is basically in the central coastal region of Vietnam.
And when I was in, prior to going over, I went to Florida, like I said, with a special train to work with the
Army, it was going to be a Joint Forces Army Air Force Strike Command as well, where the Air Force would go with the Army on certain missions and help provide close air support.
In other words, it was a complete change of what I was doing in the Air Force to going with this special group.
The ground forces in place?
Okay, what did you think you were getting yourself into?
Did you have any idea?
Oh, yeah.
I was pretty much aware of what was going to be involved as far as what we were going to be doing over there.
Of course, I don't think anybody has a real feeling for what it's going to be like until you really get there and see it.
And that's the way it has a real impact on you once you are there and see just how it can be.
So did they give you any special training and stuff before you went, as far as your job and as far as, say, the people and the culture went?
Yeah, a little bit of, I mean, we had a lot of special training as far as the job, what we'd be doing.
Like I said, that was for six weeks in Florida.
We did get some books on the culture and how the people were and what to expect, but not any real elaborate training as to what to expect from the people.
Yeah, so you were kind of surprised that you didn't know much about what to expect.
Right.
Any language training?
No, not in our group.
We had several people that were assigned to our group that had already been over there and had had, they were, you know, proficient in the language.
Yeah.
But I didn't have any.
Okay, so tell me a little bit about what your job was, what your company did.

Okay, it was to go out with the Army when they went out on a mission, search and destroy something, and if they were to come in contact with enemy forces, to call in close air support to protect our troops so that they couldn't be overrun or even help.
Okay.
Did you ever get in any big major operations?
Well, not probably what they're following some of the bigger operations.
There was nothing to do with, you know, getting what they call a firefighter or something, being in close contact with enemy forces.
So did you, you had a gun and you fought back?
Yeah, it was strictly, my role was really a defensive type role.
In other words, it was there to, I was not, what you'd say, a true combat soldier, much like the Army and Marines, where mine would just be a defensive to
so that we could provide close air support for them.
But what we got into a lot of actual combat situations with the Army forces.
So what kind of support did you call in?
It was F4C, Phantom Jets.
They could drop bombs around the area on Napalm.

you know to drive off the enemy forces how did you decide which one to bring in or did you choose or no well usually you before you went out they would tell you what um we know which squadrons would be available and where they were in approximately the time it would take for them to respond to get to you depending on how far away from those major bases you were operating and uh as far as not choosing weapons was
just bombs, basically.
Someone had napalm in those squadrons.
And they had what they called cannons, which were, you know, like a machine gun type thing.
Well, um...
Okay, let's talk about... What was a typical day like?
I mean, your strategy was search and destroy.
I mean, you went out on missions looking for...
There was the Army's purpose over there.
In other words, most of the time when we went on operation, we would be airlifted by helicopter to a specific area.
A lot of times we would be operating with other units.
In other words, they would pick up in a certain area where they felt there might be a heavy concentration of enemy forces and they would be trying to either
you know, to circle them or to drive them off.

And there may be other units being placed strategically in other areas on a, you know, or they would have a big overall map and they would be placed and try to all be coming together, going through a valley, you know, you'd be on one side, they'd be on the other, and trying to come in contact with them.
And so once you make contact with the enemy,
That's when we were calling them.
You know, we tried to identify where their positions were and calling the air strikes on them.
Did you ever land in a hot LZ, as they said?
Yeah, there was one time that we actually went in a hot LZ.
What was it like?
Well, it's, I mean, that's probably, it's just so, you know, very scary because you just don't know where anything's coming from.
Yeah.
So it's, the whole thing is just so much confusing.
And we actually got into a coma situation, and that's the thing that struck me the most, was the chaos and the confusion that's around me, and everything happening so quickly.
Yeah, okay.
Did you ever have any contact with ARVN?
Yeah, we had several times there would be some ARVN troops with us.
So what were your feelings about them?
Were they confident?
No, I have probably real strong negative feelings about them and how they operated.
We were there to do all the work, and they would bring them in at times just to be there for the operations so that they could kind of get the publicity and credit for some of the operations.
But I think there was a lot of corruption, and that there was
The officers, it was very class-oriented over there that the people that had any money in the world to do those were all the officers.
And the soldiers were just the poor people of the nation that were just put in there where they wanted to be alive.
Yeah.
So were there many cases where you and the flight guard would run?
No, we had one situation where we were resupplying a
on our base, and we were given some supplies, and this was on what they call C-130s.
It's a cargo type aircraft, and we had several trying to get on the planes to get out with us after we dropped off the supplies, trying to leave.
And just in general, anything I saw with them, I just wasn't impressed with them.
They were solely relying on us and everything that the United States would do.
They weren't really doing their fair share.
It was their own country.
They weren't going to do much about it.
They weren't any match for the D.C. or for the NBA regular season?
No, not in my opinion.
But, I mean, we didn't have that much contact with them on a regular basis, but a few times I did see them, but it was not the best we did.
Yeah, okay.
What about the Vietnamese people?
Did you have a lot of contact with them at all?
Yeah, several times you'd go into villages and stuff, and that's the thing I think you wonder about most is that
They're just in the middle of it.
It would be like being here in Kingwood and having troops coming through at any given time.
They're just basic villagers and stuff that want to go on with their daily life.
When you went through these villages, did you
Did you leave them intact, the group you were with, or did you go through it?
No, typically we would just try to clear the area, what they call a secure area, for the people that were there.
And not, we weren't involved in any of that.
Yeah.
Some of the stuff you can see right here.
Were you aware of, or in the area that you were in, a lot of times during the day the area was secure for the United States, and at night the D.C. would come through?
Right, yeah.
So did that happen a lot in the area you were in?
That's what we hear.
I mean, at times, you know, the area would be an unsecured area, and that's basically what meant that, you know, it could be...
you know, be fine during the day, in daylight hours and stuff.
And when we went there, we'd see what we infiltrated there, you know, just like we were during the daytime.
So there was supposedly a lot of that in different areas, too.
So do you think that the basic common village are just put up with whatever was there?
Right.
I think they tolerated it.
It was just a matter of survival.
I mean, they didn't feel like it was to their benefit to, you know, resist those via comms.
organized.
Obviously, they resisted the U.S. and I think that's what led to some of the complete destruction of the villages.
You know, they were just trying to get along with it and go along with their life.
And I think the same thing would happen to them if they had resisted Vietnam.
And they would probably just do the same thing, destroy the village, just totally start it.
Anyway, as it happened, it was just people that were just trying to hopefully have those boats that people would pass through and they would be left alone.
Yeah, yeah.
In the time that you were there, were they still trying the pacification program at all?
Were they still doing the win the hearts and the minds of the people?
Yeah, I guess there was some of it going on.
And I think that's where at times they were trying to get the South Vietnamese out more involved to look, you know, at least look like they were.
being active in the war for their own country.
What about the leadership that you had?
Were they qualified?
Oh yeah, I feel it.
I'm military.
Yeah, I'm military.
Oh yeah, I dig it.
The groups that I was in, where I was being qualified, we had a lot of specialized training.
It was kind of a specialized group.
So I think everybody felt confident in the troops that we had when we went on an operation.
You know, well-prepared, had a lot of backup.
Right.
So you, so your group wasn't, you didn't get fresh troops 17, 18 years old right out, right out of base?
No.
I mean, I was, I guess I was 21 when I went there.
I mean, we had some young people in it, but once they were, once we were in our group, it was, you know, well-trained and well-organized and, you know, we had a lot of support, so.
Okay.
So there was no problems with, a lot of times you hear problems about the careerism of the officers?
just, you know, trying to get their stamp on their record that they were in combat and leave?
No, I don't, I mean, I, you know, we didn't really see that, uh, that, you know, I don't feel like there's really anything going on out there.
Okay.
Um, what about drugs?
Were they there?
Were they around?
Well, yeah, they were.
I guess, um, one thing that, um,
Again, because of our, I think our group was somewhat specialized in that there was, nobody would tolerate the use of drugs within our group.
And I think prior to going over, everybody that was selected probably was, probably had been screened to one way or another that there wouldn't be any potheads and dopeheads in our outfit.
And because I think everybody felt that it was highly important that you couldn't have that type of person in our group.
Yeah, we always heard that there was a lot of drugs and stuff going on, but it wouldn't have been tolerated in our group.

Anybody that didn't have it or was suspected of it would have been sent out of our group to another group because we just felt it was too important to make sure that everybody was operating like a full bag.
Okay.
So we didn't have any problems with that out there.
So do you know anybody that had fun with the actual drugs?
Not personally, just other than what you hear and see.
But we didn't have any of it.
Okay.
Well, since you were in the special joint team, how was it commanded?
Was it under Air Force or was it under the Army?
It was under the Army because it was under the Air Force Strike Command, but it wasn't under operation without us there and support groups.
So you followed the leadership of the Army and did what they did.
Okay.
Okay.
You were there until October of 67, right?
Right.
Okay.
So you were there a few months before Tet.
Right.
Did you see any of that coming?
No.
No.
I think everything, you know, you kind of operate as a smaller unit and really don't have a feel for what's going on in the big picture of, you know, different parts of the country and such.
Yeah.
So when you came back, how was it?
How were you greeted?
How were people treating you then?
Well, it's funny.
The day I came back, there was some type of protest where people, I don't know, something with a driver on them, a driver with headlights on, protesting.
I don't know what the exact protest of that particular war was.
I mean, on that day, it was, I mean, it was still a...
protesting and a lot, you know, it hadn't really, um, escalated into, you know, this was 1967.
I think that was probably the earlier time the protests were starting to escalate and get, you know, really, you know, more and more involved with students becoming more and more involved later on.
Um, in general, I mean, it was just good driving back, you know, just
That's the one thing that was kind of frustrating, that you just left, you put in your time, and then you left, and nothing over there happened.
accomplished or finalized and just put your time in so now you could leave.
That was some of the frustrations, just leaving everything behind and the people that you knew and the villages that you knew.
But in the United States, like I say, you're just glad to be back.
There was no big thing about it, whether you had been there or not there.
I guess everybody, everything was kind of low key.
We just didn't talk much about it.
Okay.
Well, what was your opinion then on the years for the duty commandment?
Well, overall, I guess, I felt that it helped our troops more than anything.
I mean, the overall, whether it helped the troops or not,

situation I know, but looking back it probably didn't have that much of an impact, but I mean as our group, I think we helped in helping our own soldiers to survive and such, but whether or not it really had an impact didn't do much for their country in the war.
It probably didn't make much difference either way.
We just, we had the film, and I'm just sure it helped support our fighting troops.
So was your group fluid at all?
I mean, did you receive people?
In the middle, I mean, you know, did your group go as a group and stay at home, or were you constantly receiving reinforcements?
Yeah, well, our group did, our Air Force group did, and then we would operate with other Army troops.
At times, you didn't always operate with the exact same Army forces, so that you saw some of the turnover of troops coming in and going out, you know, when they went on an operation.
The troops that had been here a long time, it was obvious.
You could tell who had been here a while and who was new.
But, you know, we as a whole stayed together.
But we operated with different, some of the newer groups.
So we saw some of the rotation of the troops.
So was that bad?
Not especially so.
Um...
So did you ever get involved in any way with any anti-war things?
No, no.
Did you ever become something?
No, no, no.
Why do you think that's people that did, people that protested the war?
At the time, I was very, you know, very hostile, you know, not aggressive towards anybody.
I felt angry towards them and everything.
But then as I, you know, looking back and stuff, I think they...
probably had just as much right and probably maybe even a little more knowledgeable about what was going on over there and obviously
You know, they had their own opinions about it.
They didn't feel that it was the best war.
Yeah.
So I don't have any hard feelings towards them now at all.
Well, that's my one thing, by the way.
She didn't bother me at the time.
I mean, you know, she had her feelings about it and expressed her feelings about it.
And the war did end up being just a political, you know,
disaster over there anyways.
I mean, if we really didn't go in here militarily to do what we were supposed to do and had those objectives, I think we could have won the war.
We kept it a free country, but I think, you know, people are, I don't know, while you're not, I guess you're still not truly free people.
I don't know if they're better off, but at least there's not a major war going on in the U.S., so you wonder maybe they are better off without all that conflict on a day-to-day basis going on.
So did you know anybody that was, that they ran to him?
No.
How do you know people that did that?
Well, again, I guess the main thing would be you'd have to know what their true convictions were if they really were just doing it to you.
dogs to the draft because they didn't want to, you know, defend their country and stand up for the rights of their country.

You know, I think that they probably themselves feel bad about it, but if they really believed in why they were going, and they didn't want to get in that war, but it was because they didn't feel that that war wasn't right,
you know, from an overall perspective that, you know, they probably feel just the same as we do about the way I've helped them, you know, for not being drawn into that thing.
And, you know, as long as they're, they would have to know what their true convictions of why they left the country.
But I don't have any, you know, hard feelings towards anybody that did it.
Everybody had to make their own decision to do what they wanted to do.
Yeah, I mean, I think he's the one who has to live with it.
He probably was just dodging the draft because he didn't want to get involved and had the money and the power to do that.
But, I mean, there's plenty of that going on here and just like I'm sure what's going on here.
I mean, I think that's what...
Overall, I'm so weak.
On a personal basis, it doesn't matter because they're the ones that have to live with it.
I did what I did to feel comfortable with it for the reasons that I wanted to.
I thought I was helping those people and able to help our own students.
I feel good about what I did.
Okay.
Well, in your opinion, do you think that we could have won the war?
Oh, yeah.
Militarily, I definitely think we could have won the war.
I got so bogged down in the politics of the war.
There was a lot of rules and stuff going on over there that you couldn't do this.
You couldn't bomb the planes.
The North Vietnamese planes that were on the ground in North Vietnam, they had to be fine.
You couldn't go into this area.
You couldn't go into that area.
So, and I mean, when you think of the, I mean, you'd have, as you study, then you'll see the type of equipment and the forces that we have, just with the air power, all the helicopters,
you know, the technology that we have and these people are running, you know, weapons down on, you know, old bicycles and everything.
There's no way that they should have been able to win that war.
But militarily, to win that, it probably would have caused so much more destruction.
And to have people that didn't have, you know, I don't know how to evaluate whether it was or not, but
I think, you know, if it was just a true military war, we definitely should have and could have won the war.
So, who do you blame for not letting people and the politicians win?
Yes.
For not letting the military fight the war?
Right, I think they're all government people that were looking out for their best interests.
and letting it drag on as long as it did.
I think that's what finally got all the students where they got involved and felt that it was a useless effort and it shouldn't be continued.
And I think at that point they were right.
You know, if we weren't going to do it, then we ought to get out of there, not just let it be a

have a PMS one, I think, in the late 60s, early 70s, why they're having so much morale involved with our own troops, because there was so much conflict here about it, and they were going over, you know, people don't want to die for something they felt was a useless cause at that time.
That was a lot of, you know, 66, when I first went over, so it was, you know, there was still a lot of
people felt it was a worthwhile effort to help that country.
That was a real dinner.
Helped those people win freedom.
So was there a time when you thought that maybe
What you were doing wasn't helping the people?
Maybe you shouldn't have been there?
Not while I was in the service.
After, later on, you had some doubts that, not so much that you shouldn't have been there, but that you were used by the government for their own use.
That you weren't really, couldn't accomplish what you really tried to do there for.
You don't want to handle all those second thoughts that are no longer in the military.
So you never went through any period where you didn't want to be there, you didn't, I mean...
Right, I mean, not, uh, not even for a time because I wanted to do it just because it was so scary, but, uh, not from, uh...
Uh, moral or, uh...
Right.
Yeah.
We still have that conviction that we were there for a good purpose and that we were doing something.
How do you think we could have gone to war?
What should we have done?

I would say, I guess, just that we would have had to have been more forceful in the use of our weapons and just could have really, you know, probably with more direct attacks on North Vietnam and on their leaders.
I just think that had we built up even quicker and more rapidly and stronger earlier in the war, we could have brought that to a later finish sooner.
So what you were doing, was it working?
Could you see progress?
Yeah, I would say that what we were there for as a group that I was with
It was to protect our own forces so that they couldn't be overrun.
And obviously, the fact that I came back with one on one because we never.
So I would say that the purpose of our outfit, what we were doing was successful.
And that's why I feel good about it because I felt that we accomplished what we were there for, was to protect us.
Like I said, it was a defensive, to protect our own troops.
Did you ever lose anybody any time during that?
Well, yeah, we, I mean, we had casualties, but then our outfits obviously gone during some conflict, so, you know, we just lost people.
Were you ever hit?
No, unfortunately, as far as, you know, see somebody, when somebody does die, it's, that's, you see it.
Do you think then that rolling thunder was anything that was working, bombing North Vietnam?
Maybe we should have done more, not restricted maybe?
Yeah, I think more.
I think that would have brought the war home more to them.
That would have caused some turmoil within their country.
They could get the war over, possibly forever, or...
about after Tet?
A lot of people have said that maybe if we had hit them right after Tet when they were weak, maybe we could have won.
What do you think?
I guess that there's probably some validity to that.
And, you know, we, like I said, militarily, I think we had the power to do pretty much what we wanted to had we used our forces, you know, stronger in places.
were we not using our technology to our advantage
So in your opinion, do you think we should have been there?
I mean, we were right, our original way anyway.
I think our original thing was stopping the flow of communism and keeping our country free and letting them be the choice.
I mean, we were there supposedly as a support group for their forces to defend themselves.
But it slowly turned to where they were just letting us do all the fighting
and they wanted us to win the war for them.
And so I think there was a lot of their own internal problems that they didn't have the true commitment to the war that would have been required for a country to win its own war.
That, along with the political thing that our government was pointing at, was the overall reason for our failure.
So was there a point when you saw the tide change and you thought that maybe we should have gotten out?
I think it was not a, I don't know, to me it seems a certain point.

Because you were there, and you just put in your time, and then you leave, and of course, like I mentioned earlier, that's the frustration there, that you're glad to leave, but you wonder about, you have, you know, you wonder about the people that you've left behind, the villages that you've got to go, and, you know, whatever happens to them.
So there's frustration happening.
No, I didn't see any specific point where I felt it would change.

It was more seeing it as being involved here in the United States with the dissension within the United States, because that built, that would have to build that swing that all the people hit, that by the end of the year, you know, the people that had, you know, family and friends and relatives being killed, and I just felt as if to see it continuing on, that it wouldn't, you know, win cars.
And so, to me, I just heard it as a slow, gradual,
When you were there, did you ever get any feelings that you weren't, the people back home weren't supporting you?
Were you aware of any of that stuff, any anti-war things then?
It was still early.
Yeah, it was still early.
At that time, I guess I just perceived it as those were the people that didn't want to deal with the military and fight.
I mean, that's probably how I perceived it at that time.
And it wasn't really as much of a...
an anti-war movement.
Those were people that just didn't want to go to the law and use that as a front.
I'm sure there was some of that, but like I said, I don't really know what the person's true convictions are, whether or not they were anti-war or just against themselves going over there.
Okay, we've talked a lot in my class about movies and things.
Are there any movies that you've seen in Vietnam about Vietnam that are realistic that even come close to one?
Well, I guess in general, some of them, all of them that I've seen have some parts that are pretty realistic and some unrealistic.
So it's hard to say in particular what we've done.
There were parts in pop films now that I've shot that were
very realistic.
I haven't seen full metal jacks.
I haven't seen full metal jacks, but you can put some apocalypse now.
There's some parts that are very realistic in here.
And there were some things that were
We had in the war that a lot of people might see it and not be able to perceive it as being realistic.
It was the way you went in and out of the war so quickly with these helicopters.
in Desjardins situation and then right away we'd be back out and back to our main base in Hemero.
I didn't want to be too long on the compass.
I'm hoping it still was a military base in a war zone, but we were withdrawn from the media turmoil quite quickly.
So it was that off and on type thing.
Did you ever know anybody that, as they say, went native?
Not, not, didn't see that coming.
Um, yeah.
Can you tell us more about, uh, well just, just what, what you did, I mean.
In your growth, I mean, you could just spend all, you'd be helicoptered into an area.
And from there, what do you do?

Well, then you just, before you went out, you wouldn't do it with a, you'd have a, you know, they'd bring everybody in and tell them what the purpose of the operation was and how they expected it to go and what they...
What was available to us?
to accomplish that, what our units were, what our military were operating in the area, what the overall purpose of that particular operation was.
And then they would just go out and fly into this area.
And the Army, like I say, they were the ones that were actually doing the operation.
They, you know, helped us through an area that they were trying to secure or declare.
And what they were, what the particular purpose of that operation was, you know, we would just be with them.
And, uh, he worked many times and we didn't make any contact with the army.
So it was just, you know, I mean, you would be out and nothing would basically happen on the, you know, all of us.
When we did come in contact with them, that's when we, through radio contact with our own air forces, more than strikes at different areas around us to both cut off the enemy from escaping and try to

You know, you would notify the other units that where they were operating, sometimes they would be able to come where they were because of the distance involved and brought into a strategic flanking of them, you know, trying to serve one way or another.
So, you know, it was just...
you know, basic military operations.
The purpose was we would just be operating with the Army.

And then when we came under fire, we would be strictly defensive under fire, you know, hopefully help hold back the Tide and the forces with the court and the S-Rates with the down route to accomplish defensive defenses like that.
Okay, so how often did you run into these?
Probably one out of three or four times.
That one would go out.
Maybe one out of three or four times.
Because I think most of the time that we were pursuing work, they were trying to be evasive and they were not one of them.
take us on, take on our groups, because I think they most likely are the forces that they have.
So I mean, we would probably try and always be after the groups that were the guerrilla-type warfare in the Viet Cong.
We would never pursue the North Vietnamese armed regularcy.
There was only one operation of ours that wouldn't fail.
I mean, in our briefings, we were told that it was going to be in use.
Most of the time, we were after guerrilla warfare, you know, re-economy type.
And so, I think they, most of the time, they would try to evade us.
So, they didn't, it wasn't like you were put in, you were being directed.
